    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-27T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-27T15:00:00-05:00" n="705"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d705">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/1214: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-27T23:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 27, 1943—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 28—12:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2337. Reference your 1447, December 23.<note n="82" xml:id="d705fn82">See
                        footnote 72, <ref target="#pg_849">p. 849</ref>.</note> I think you should
                    bear in mind that the Soviet officials are using the Kharkov trials in external
                    propaganda as a means of separating the front line troops from the troops in the
                    rear. You will note that the three Germans selected had seen no service at the
                    front and much is made of this in the Soviet leaflets dropped on German troops
                    at the Russian front.</p>
                <p>It would be helpful to know why the War Department does not believe that a
                    campaign of publicity based on the Kharkov trials is desirable at this time.</p>
                <p>What additional information do you wish from Moscow on this subject?</p>
                <p>Repeated to London.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
